I do think, however, that ‚ÄòMr. Right Now‚Äô is dismissive. And not just toward men: The very existence of the term presupposes that all women are looking for Mr. Right, which feels rather 1950s-ish. 

Over Christmas, I was invited into the kids‚Äô room to play with dolls. Barbie didn‚Äôt have Ken, but there was a Ron (from Harry Potter). While I allowed Ron to cook Barbie a nice candlelight dinner and draw her a bath, I set up Barbie with her feet up on the sofa, laptop in hand, surrounded by books, mountain-climbing gear, and her go bag. I made sure my nieces thrice-removed knew that in my book Barbie needed to be the hero of her own story. 

